Permit Prediction in Philadelphia, PA

Jamie Song, Gabriel Hernandez

2023-12-16

Note: To view our Pechakucha presentation focusing more on the use case for this model, please see this YouTube video.

1 Introduction

As we move along corridors and spaces in a city, we can tell where there is new development going on and where there is not. This is because the built environment is a symbol for processes of change. Some of these processes are related to the systems of power that govern a given site at a particular point in time. Market forces at the time of construction impart meaning to a site, which can be as simple as – at this point in time, someone wanted to build a new structure and they applied for a permit.

The housing market of a city ranges from neighborhood to neighborhood, so when a particular neighborhood has a high amount of permits – meaning that people are either building or tearing down a structure – we can infer that it is an area with high development activity. We decided to analyze the pattern of permit applications for the City of Philadelphia to identify where there are development “hotspots.” Hotspots are locations where there are statistically significant clusters of high permit counts. We also wanted to explore the predictive power of two approaches to identifying future hotspots in the city.

We were motivated to perform this analysis because of its implication for activism and the potential of the analysis to confirm the development that we see around the city. In meetings with the Director of Development at Nehemiah HDFC, a NYC-based affordable development company, we learned that this type of analysis can provide a basis for considering where to target neighborhood-wide rezoning campaigns. Neighborhood-wide rezonings can make it easier to increase the supply of housing with the stroke of a pen, and they can protect the roots of long-term residents and businesses in the community. Thus, if our model is accurate, then it gives lead organizers more power to carry out actions on behalf of a gentrifying community. We seek to create a model that identifies communities experiencing high concentrations of development and that uncovers where there is latent potential for more permit applications.

We set up two models, a long-term and a short-term. The purpose was to compare their performance and to know if a few years worth of permit data would be enough to accurately predict permit hotspots. The success of the short-term model would incentivize communities to advocate for a properly formatted permit database. With development areas identified it will be easier to conduct neighborhood-wide and other small scale rezoning initiatives.

Our approach to the model creation process starts with filtering the permits dataset to select the ones that we believe are related to development. We will then use geocomputation techniques to develop indicators that can predict the count of permits per unit of analysis. We will then explore the correlation of our features and create a regression model to cross-validate by neighborhood. Lastly, we will predict future permit counts and identify hotspots using local Moran’s I cluster analysis. We will conduct the same procedure for two different time frames and compare their performance to determine at which scale we can best predict significant hotspots of permits.

2 Long-Term Model Methods and Results

We will begin our analysis with what we call our long-term model. This version of our permit hotspot prediction model will take the total permit counts for the 2009-2018 period and predict the 2019 permit counts across the City of Philadelphia. The short-term model will use a shorter time period of permits, the 2021-2022 period to predict for permits in 2023. We will otherwise use the same engineered features in each model, which will be related to the relationship between a neighborhood’s position and socio-demographic changes across the City of Philadelphia between 2013-2019.

Again, the purpose here is to investigate how accurately we can predict permit counts, and then whether we need 2 years of data or 10 to identify permit hotspots for a following year.

2.1 Data Sources

Below, we load data to build our permit prediction model. The datasets and corresponding sources are as follows:

  • Geographies
    • Neighborhoods: Azavea
    • Boundaries: City of Philadelphia
  • Dependent Variable
    • Permits: City of Philadelphia
  • Predictor Variables
    • Transit stations: City of Philadelphia
    • Demographic variables at block group level: US Census Bureau

In selecting permits, we inherently introduce bias into our analysis. There is a wide range of “type of work” values in the permit data but we wanted to focus on those that added new structures, demolished others, added value to the structure, demolished the interior, or other techniques used to make a development projects work. These are just a few examples and we point out others below. We had to interpret the overlap between the type of work designation whether it came from the department of buildings or the zoning office for the same place. Should only one department be used? We took the multiple observations as an indicator of the willingness of developers to jump over multi-tiered bureaucratic barriers to development.

We used a query that filtered for any of the following permit type-related terms and more (see code):

  • FULL = Building permit - Demolition related
  • INTERI = Interior demolition
  • ADD = Zoning permit, add things to the building from structures to appliances/tech such as antennas
  • SHELL - Building Permit - Construction of structure before separate permits for occupancy and fitout are done
  • ENTIRE = Building Permit - New Construction related
  • FRAME - Building Permit - Steel structures for building construction
  • NEWCON = Zoning permit related - New construction
  • COMDEM = Zoning permit - Complete demolition
  • FITOUT = Tenants building out unit provided by developer

For demographic variables, we chose to import 2013 and 2019 block group level data. We wanted to work into our long-term model the relationship between neighborhood changes in demographics with the development intensity. We were limited to calculating percent changes between those years because block group level data was not available prior to 2013, and block group geometries changed after 2019 because of 2020 Census redistricting. The resulting indicators that we worked into our model for this subset of years are:

  • Change in White proportion of population
  • Change in vacancy rate
  • Change in ICE score (economic only)
  • Percent change in median home value

A Note on ICE:

The ICE metric was developed by social science and epidemiology researchers to capture “extremes of privilege and deprivation” as well as measure both economic and racial segregation. It is calculated using the following formula:

\[ICE=\frac{(A−P)}{T}\]

Where A represents the number of households belonging to the privileged extreme, while P is the number of households who belong to the deprived extreme in a given area. T is the total number of households in that area.

ICE can take any value between -1 and 1; a value of 1 indicates that all residents are in the “privileged” group, and a value of −1 indicates that all residents are in the most “deprived” group. For this model, the privileged group is defined as households with incomes over 100,000 USD, and the deprived group is defined as households with incomes below 25,000 USD.

2.2.4 Local Moran’s I Hotspot Engineered Features

To analyze the relationship between our permits point data and the changes observed in the block group level ACS data between 2013-2019, we used local Moran’s I to our advantage. For each variable that we analyzed the distribution of percent changes, we used local Moran’s I to identify its statistically significant hotspots across Philadelphia. We then calculated the distance of each neighborhood to the nearest hotspot for each indicator’s hotspot and added it to our model. We believe that these indicators serve as a part of the “exposure” that affects the observed total “development” permit counts across Philadelphia.

The indicators created in this process capture changes that took place between 2013-2019 and that we think are related to development, such as the percent changes in vacant units, poverty rates, white population as a function of historically disproportionate access to capital, and ICE scores. Understanding the limitations of arguing for using the same exposure period for both models, we recall from in-class guidance that what matters is that the model is powerful and generalizable, not so much that the inputs are theoretically coherent. Given our results and the previous discussion about how we consider the indicators relevant to development, we feel justified in maintaining them in both models.

2.2.4.1 Local Moran’s I Feature Engineering - Existing Permit Hotspots & Socio-Demographic Variables

The following graphics follow the creation of permit hotspots. The local Moran’s I value at each fishnet cell indicates the extent of significant spatial clustering of permit counts around that cell. P-values are calculated using Monte Carlo simulations and represent the probability of obtaining the same spatial distribution of permit counts if permits are distributed randomly. Therefore, very small p-values indicate hotspots, which we identified at a \(\alpha = 0.000001\) significance level.

final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$totalPermits, 
                           final_net.weights, 
                           zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
                as.data.frame()

final_net.localMorans.Permit <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(PermitCount = totalPermits, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.000001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans.Permit$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = nhoods, color = "transparent", fill = "gray80") +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans.Permit, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(option = "E", name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Moran's I statistics, Total Permits"))

To address challenges in using block group level data in fishnet cell level analyses, particularly incongruence between block group and fishnet cell geometries, we generated hotspots for variables related to socio-demographic changes using local Moran’s I at a \(\alpha = 0.01\) significance level. We then calculated the distance from each fishnet cell to its closest hotspot. We also use the previously generated local Moran’s I hotspots of permits at a \(\alpha = 0.000001\) significance level, then engineered an indicator that equaled the distance from an individual fishnet cell to its nearest permit hotspot.

We believe that including these relationships between places and hotspots captures spatial relationships that influence where there are opportunities for development in the first place. As mentioned earlier, development is an opportunistic undertaking. As latent opportunities become viable, development finds itself in new places, and the pack of speculative developers follow suit.

Understanding how hotspots are created in the first place could be very important to the work of cities, potentially leading to neighborhood wide rezonings that are programmed in part to entice development. This path of inquiry can answer important questions such as: how do we bring development to areas where there isn’t currently? And what neighborhood characteristics are leading to more investments in hotspot areas?

phlblockgroups.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(phlblockgroups.sf), queen=TRUE)
phlblockgroups.weights <- nb2listw(phlblockgroups.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

phlblockgroups.sf <- phlblockgroups.sf %>% 
  mutate(ICE.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(phlblockgroups.sf$changeICE1319, 
                             phlblockgroups.weights)[,5] <= 0.01, 1, 0),
         HVal.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(phlblockgroups.sf$pctchangeHVal1319, 
                             phlblockgroups.weights)[,5] <= 0.01, 1, 0),
         Vacant.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(phlblockgroups.sf$pctchangeVacant1319, 
                             phlblockgroups.weights)[,5] <= 0.01, 1, 0),
         White.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(phlblockgroups.sf$pctchangeWhite1319, 
                             phlblockgroups.weights)[,5] <= 0.01, 1, 0),
         )
final_net <- final_net %>%
    mutate(Permit.isSig = ifelse(localmoran(final_net$totalPermits, 
                             final_net.weights)[,5] <= 0.000001, 1, 0)) 
final_net <- final_net %>%
    mutate(Permit.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),
                            st_coordinates(st_centroid(filter(final_net, 
                                                              final_net$Permit.isSig == 1))),1),
           ICE.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),
                            st_coordinates(st_centroid(filter(phlblockgroups.sf, 
                                                              phlblockgroups.sf$ICE.isSig == 1))),1),
           HVal.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),
                            st_coordinates(st_centroid(filter(phlblockgroups.sf, 
                                                              phlblockgroups.sf$HVal.isSig == 1))),1),
           Vacant.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),
                            st_coordinates(st_centroid(filter(phlblockgroups.sf, 
                                                              phlblockgroups.sf$Vacant.isSig == 1))),1),
           White.isSig.dist = nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(final_net)),
                            st_coordinates(st_centroid(filter(phlblockgroups.sf, 
                                                              phlblockgroups.sf$White.isSig == 1))),1),
           )

2.2.4.2 Moran’s I Hotspot Distance-From Variable Map

The following maps visualize the distance-to-hotspot features that we engineered. Of note, none of the features have a spatial pattern that closely resemble those of other features, lowering the likelihood of collinearity in our model. We used these indicators in our long-term and short-term models, believing that we were using the city-wide experience of change to predict permit counts in Philadelphia. Again the change is calculated at the census block group level between 2013 and 2019 using ACS 5-Year estimates.

final_net %>%
  dplyr::select(Permit.isSig.dist, 
                ICE.isSig.dist, 
                HVal.isSig.dist, 
                Vacant.isSig.dist, White.isSig.dist) %>%
  pivot_longer(where(is.numeric), names_to = "Variable", values_to = "Value") %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill=Value), color=NA) +
    scale_fill_viridis(name="NN Distance", option="E") +
    labs(title="Distance to highly significant hotspots",
         subtitle = "For four geospatial features") +
    facet_wrap(~Variable, nrow = 1) +

2.3 Correlation and Relationships Analysis

After exploring our features and generating new ones for our models, we set out to study the possible relationships. This analysis assists us in deciding which variables we will use in our poisson regression model. We began with a correlation matrix, pictured below.

The relationship between the changes in housing values and the proximity to permit hotspots stands out to us. There is a strong positive correlation, which highlights what development can mean from an economic perspective: investment in a stock of housing that increases its value, reflected in higher rent of land prices. Moreover, we see that the total count of permits is strongly correlated with the distance to hotspots. That is easy to understand in hindsight but it is worth nothing that this is a reflection of how trendy and concentrated development, as an aspect of every city, is. The work done in hotspots shapes a specific part of the total urban fabric for a long time to come, and then it shifts to another part of town.

2.4 Modeling

To get more insight into the performance of our model, we set up two models, with different predictor variables. One contained the permit hotspots and the distance to those permit hotspots and the other excluded them.

The rest of the indicators that we engineered, such as the the distances to socioeconomic change hotspots and to commercial corridors, will be present in both.

reg.vars.permit <- c("Permit.isSig.dist", "Permit.isSig",
                     "White.isSig.dist",
              "ICE.isSig.dist","HVal.isSig.dist","Vacant.isSig.dist",
              "fn_dist_comm")

reg.vars <- c("White.isSig.dist",
              "ICE.isSig.dist","HVal.isSig.dist","Vacant.isSig.dist",
              "fn_dist_comm")

We then performed two separate leave-one-group-out spatial cross validations (LOGO-CV) to test the performance of the models. The hold-out groups in our test were the neighborhoods of Philadelphia, which we joined and assigned to each fishnet cell for the purpose of this analysis.

set.seed(888)

reg.permit.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
    dataset = final_net_reg,
    id = "name",                           
    dependentVariable = "totalPermits",
    indVariables = reg.vars.permit) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = name, totalPermits, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
    dataset = final_net_reg,
    id = "name",

    indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = name, totalPermits, Prediction, geometry)

We observe that adding the distance to a permit hotspot helps to reduce our errors, increasing the frequency of folds with 0-3 errors. This provides support for the idea that the distance to permit hotspots is an important indicator of future development activity.

There are less outliers when the distance to permit hotspots is included. However, we still have outliers. It could be that our model underpredicts in areas with high counts of development permits. The next set of maps will to help clarify where we are getting our highest errors.

2.6 Long-Term Model: Generalizability Test

To test the generalizability of our model, we examined its performance across block groups split by income. A household’s income level is a key determinant of whether its residents are able to afford to pay rent or property taxes and avoid being displaced. It also plays a part in defining one’s socioeconomic class. Thus, we split block groups by whether they were above or below the median of block group level median household income ($41,426).

The below summary table shows that, again, the mean of errors are lower in the model that includes permit hotspot related features. It also shows that our model underpredicts permit incidence in block groups above the median and slightly overpredicts permit counts in block groups under the median.

The average margin of errors, however, is quite small. That there is a discrepancy in the errors means that our model could be fine-tuned further, but it is still predicting well.

phlblockgroups.sf <- phlblockgroups.sf %>%
  mutate(IncomeContext = ifelse(MedHHInc19 > 41416, "Above_Median", "Below_Median"))

reg.summary %>% 
    st_centroid() %>%
    st_join(phlblockgroups.sf) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    st_drop_geometry() %>%
    group_by(Regression, IncomeContext) %>%
    summarize(mean.Error = mean(Error, na.rm = T)) %>%
    spread(IncomeContext, mean.Error) %>%
    kable(caption = "Mean Error by Block Group Income Context") %>%
    kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>%
  row_spec(1, color = "white", background = "#383120") %>%  
  row_spec(2, color = "black", background = "#de9f00")

3 Short-Term Model Methods and Results

Now we will create and analyze a short-term model to predict total counts of development related permit across Philadelphia for 2023. We refer to this model as short-term because we will only train it on permit counts between 2021-2022.

The model will include the same 2013-2019 socioeconomic hotspot-distance indicators that we used in the long-term model. The key difference here is that we are only using 2 years worth of permit data (2021-2022) instead of 10 years.

The purpose is to evaluate the cost of beginning to document permit types in jurisdictions interested in defining their hotspots for future planning initiatives at the neighborhood level.

Using this break also made sense because of the COVID-19 pandemic and resulting lockdown. Moreover, as we mentioned before, the type of work value definitions were changed after 2020. The observations of permits between 2021-2022 made sense to use for our short-term analysis, skipping the value of 2020 as an abnormal year.

3.1 Fishnet of Permits 2021-2022

Again, we start with an an exploratory analysis. We create a map of the count of permits per fishnet cell.

This is one way that our model is different from the long-term model. Our permit hotspot distance-from indicator is based on the permits that we are using for this model, not the 2009-2018.

3.4.1 Histogram and Summary Table

The spread of errors is narrower and closer to the mean when the permit hotspot distance indicator is included. Outliers are decreased and the frequency of extremely low values increases compared to when it is not included.

One difference between these distributions is that there are no clear outstanding errors. We hypothesize that this is because our total permit count is over a short period of years. The implication is that in the long-term model we underpredict at the high percentile of observed permit counts because some cells have multi-year accumulations built into their values.

Overall, although we would like to optimize for the least amount of error, we think that the short-term model performs similarly to the long-term model.

Below we can compare the maps of errors for the long-term model and the short-term model.   cbind(
    aggregate(
      dplyr::select(cpfinal_23.sf) %>% mutate(totalPermits = 1), ., sum) %>%
    mutate(totalPermits = replace_na(totalPermits, 0))) %>%
  dplyr::select(label, Risk_Category, totalPermits)

permit_reg_sf_23 <-
  filter(reg.summary_2122, Regression == "Spatial LOGO-CV permit dist") %>%
  mutate(label = "Risk Predictions",
         Risk_Category = ntile(Prediction, 100),

           Risk_Category >= 90 ~ "90% to 100%",

3.5.1 Kernel Density Comparison: Bar Chart

We think that the bar chart is a good way to compare the performance of our model to the kernel density approach. One thing that we like here is that our model does better than kernel density across all percentiles of count values except for the highest ones.

We think that in implication of our model is the ability to detect mid-range activity of development because they could be emerging areas that could turn into hotspots. It would be important to be able to identify them so it is good that we outperform the kernel density prediction in the other categories.

We believe that the kernel density outperforms our short-term model at the highest category because it is dependent on concentrations can better anticipate those areas. Our models sacrifice the ability to predict the highest counts of permits for the ability to predict for the other ranges of values. As we will see, we do not lose the ability to detect future hotspots of development in the process.

The performance of this short-term model appears to match and even exceed that of the long-term model when compared to kernel density, suggesting that short-term phases for permit prediction are still effective.

3.6 Short-Term Model: Predicted Permit Hotspot Map Comparison

The result of our short-term model is a permit hotspot prediction for 2023. To create these hotspots, we ran a local Moran’s I test on the 2023 permit counts that our model predicted to identify the hotspots. A walkthrough of that process is visualized below.

reg.summary.morans_2122 <- reg.summary_2122 %>%
  dplyr::filter(Regression == "Spatial LOGO-CV permit dist")

reg.summary.morans.nb_2122 <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(reg.summary.morans_2122), queen=TRUE)
reg.summary.morans.weights_2122 <- nb2listw(reg.summary.morans.nb_2122, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

local_morans_2122 <- localmoran(reg.summary.morans_2122$Prediction, 
                           reg.summary.morans.weights_2122, 
                           zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
                as.data.frame()

final_predict.localMorans.Permit_2122 <- 
  cbind(local_morans_2122, as.data.frame(reg.summary.morans_2122)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(PermitCount = Prediction, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.000001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

vars <- unique(final_predict.localMorans.Permit_2122$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = nhoods, color = "transparent", fill = "gray80") +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_predict.localMorans.Permit_2122, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(option = "E", name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Moran's I statistics, Predicted Permits 2023"))

The following comparison is the most significant in our report. Here, we have the long-term model’s predicted hotspot map on the left and the short-term model’s predicted hotspot map on the right. Again, the long-term model is based on the use of 10 years of permit data as opposed to the short-term model, which used 2 years of permit data to predicted the next available year (2019 and 2023 respectively).

They both highlight similar parts of Philadelphia as permit hotspots, but the short-term model seems to be more insightful because it has small pockets compared to large areas, indicating greater precision. One hotspot in Manayunk that existed in 2019 hotspots did not appear in 2023, which may suggest a slower pace of development in that area after the COVID-19 pandemic.

What is really important here is that we can confirm that we do not need 10 years worth of permit data to identify development hotspots in Philadelphia. Jurisdictions can embark on permit dataset creation efforts today and, within two to three years, have a verifiable way to identify their cities’ development hotspots. This can revolutionize how we target parts of a city for neighborhood wide rezonings and talk about the development that we find around us on drives and walks.

4 Discussion and Conclusion

Change is as real as life itself. When we travel around a city, we can see development happening in some places more than others, but you can organize action based on the eye test alone. Development is a process of change that shapes the built environment, alters the fabric of the city, and it functions as a vehicle for capital. Today, when people think about development they imagine gentrification. In this way, development has earned a negative connotation and communities fight to curb its forces. But we argue that development is a natural process of the city’s life and we should work with it rather than limit it totally or allow it to work freely.

In this project, we aimed to predict development hotspots in Philadelphia based on existing permit data. In doing so accurately, we are able to say that certain, specific parts of the city are undergoing development, unleashing a variety of possible actions. js - what actions were you thinking of? e.g. rezoning + …

To do this, we must develop a model that help us identify where development is happening in the city. We used OpenDataPhilly to obtain our initial permit data from 2009-2023. We defined development hotspots as areas where there were high rates of permits related to costly and large scale types of work. These hotspots reflect where investors were willing to inject their capital due to existing market forces. In doing so, they may alter the characteristics of the neighborhood and local population. We tried to capture these relationships in our prediction model through the use of changes in Philadelphia at the census block group level between 2013-2019 as indicators.

We find great value in the ability to determine development hotspots, so we wanted to know how many years worth of permits we needed in order to produce accurate predictions. To do this, we constructed and compared two models – a long-term Poisson regression model and a short-term one – to predict the total permit counts of individual fishnet cells. We used local Moran’s I to turn that data into a map of statistically significant hotspots. We ran diagnostic tests on our errors for accuracy and generalizability. The models generalize across incomes according to our results, but it is important to test more contexts in future development in order to verify how robust the model is. We were satisfied with the performance of our model but acknowledge that it could be more accurate with more data and further feature engineering to produce different predictor variables. However, the quantities of our errors are small and each model produces spatially defined hotspots that are easy to visualize and communicate.

We discovered that with just a few years worth of permit data, and engineered features related to socio-demographic changes, we could identify the city’s permit hotspots. Our analysis provides a statistically significant basis for the definition of areas in a city experiencing high rates of development. With this information we can pitch a targeted neighborhood-wide rezoning initiative in the predicted hotspots. We could wrangle development and with the stroke of a pen provide more affordable units, specify the size of businesses operating in the neighborhood, upzone, and overall make it easier to build. Ultimately, more creative ideas can emerge as they will be neighborhood-specific.

Our analysis in this project confirms what one can see on the ground in the permit hotspot areas. Because a sufficiently accurate model can be produced with only a couple of years of permit data, communities have an incentive to invest in advocating for their governments to document permit application in publicly available and easy-to-analyze formats. It would be easy to perform the analysis and identify statistically significant development hotspots. Moreover, from the perspective of a speculator, you could identify areas that are on the verge of becoming hotter hotspots and get into the market early. In shifting the conversation to development rather than gentrification, and to neighborhood wide rezonings instead of stern NIMBYism, we can plan more carefully with the forces that are present with us as we shape neighborhoods.
